  "prompt": "If I push a rod of length 0.3 million km, the other end of rod moves immediately. Would that not mean information has traveled faster than light?",
  "response": "When you push one end of a rod, the \"push\" or force applied doesn't cause the other end to move instantaneously. Instead, the force travels as a mechanical wave through the material of the rod at a finite speed. This speed is limited by the speed of sound in the material, which is much slower than the speed of light.\n\nIn practice, any mechanical wave travels through a solid object at the speed of sound specific to that material. Even in the stiffest materials, this speed is many orders of magnitude slower than the speed of light. Therefore, no information or effect can travel faster than light, and the scenario you describe would not lead to information traveling faster than light.\n\nThus, even with a rod that is theoretically perfect and impossibly rigid (which doesn't exist according to the principles of relativity), relativity does not allow for any information or influence to be transmitted faster than the speed of light.",
